                    "description": "Why did people decide to found political parties? What determined their organizational structure?  PhD research project \"The Birth of Political Mass Parties\" studies the ideas and practices of political activists who founded the first political mass parties in the second half of the 19th century. It focuses on the expectations and experiences of party leaders when they tried to combine mass organization and parliamentary politics. The project analyses three case studies: the German Social Democratic Workers` Party (Sozialdemokratische Arbeiterpartei, SDAP founded in 1869), the Dutch Antirevolutionary Party (ARP, Anti-Revolutionaire Partij, 1879) and the British National Liberal Federation (NLF, 1877).\"\n\nI am also a member of the research group \"The Promise of Organization\" under Prof. Henk te Velde and Dr. Maartje Janse and participant in the profile area \"Political Legitimacy\". In addition, I organized a best practices workshop for PhD candidates at the Institute for History.",
